Overall Summary 
price_data.py
Retrieves stock prices and fundamental data from Yahoo Finance for a list of tickers. It also calculates indicators such as RSI and prepares the data for analysis by the trading engine.
data_download.py
Downloads historical stock price and dividend data using Yahoo Finance and stores it locally for reuse. This provides the historical datasets required for portfolio analysis and backtesting.
data_retrieval.py
Loads previously stored market datasets from local files or databases. It allows the trading engine to quickly access historical price data without repeatedly downloading it.
price_service.py
Calculates portfolio values, performance metrics, dividends, and cash balances based on transaction history and historical market data. It also converts values into GBP and tracks portfolio performance over time.
universe_utils.py
Manages the stock universe by loading tickers and company information from universe.json. It allows the system to retrieve all tickers, filter them by sector, and access information about specific stocks.

For your document, you can summarise price_data.py like this:
•	Purpose: Retrieves stock price and fundamental data for a list of securities and prepares it for analysis within the trading engine.
•	Data Source: Uses the Yahoo Finance API (yfinance) to download historical price data and company fundamentals.
•	Inputs:
o	List of stock tickers (symbols)
o	Historical price data (used for calculations like RSI)
•	Batch Processing: Symbols are split into smaller batches using chunk_list() to improve performance and avoid API rate limits when downloading data.
•	Technical Indicator Calculation: Calculates the Relative Strength Index (RSI) from historical closing prices to measure momentum and identify overbought or oversold conditions.
•	Parallel Processing: Uses multithreading (ThreadPoolExecutor) to fetch company fundamentals for multiple stocks simultaneously, improving speed.
•	Output: Returns a structured dictionary containing key market and financial metrics for each stock, including price, previous close, sector, market cap, valuation ratios, and RSI.
•	Role in System: Acts as the data ingestion and preprocessing layer, providing cleaned and enriched market data that other components of the trading engine can use for analysis or strategy calculations.



File: data_download.py
•	Purpose: Downloads and stores historical stock price data and dividend information for a list of securities. This data is used by the trading engine for analysis and strategy calculations.
•	Data Source: Uses the Yahoo Finance API (yfinance) to retrieve historical market data and dividend payments for each stock.
•	Inputs:
o	List of stock tickers
o	Start date for historical data (set to December 2017)
•	Data Processing:
o	Downloads historical market data (open, high, low, close, volume).
o	Retrieves dividend data for each stock.
o	Removes timezone information to ensure consistent date indexing.
o	Aligns dividend data with market data dates.
o	Combines price and dividend data into a single dataset for each ticker.
•	Error Handling:
o	Includes retry logic to attempt downloads multiple times if an error occurs.
o	Introduces delays between requests to avoid API rate limits.
•	Data Storage:
o	The downloaded datasets are saved locally as a pickle file (downloaded_data.pkl) for faster loading later.
•	Output:
o	A dictionary where each stock ticker maps to its historical dataset containing price and dividend information.
•	Additional Functions:
o	load_saved_data() loads previously saved market data from the pickle file.
o	load_saved_exchange_rates() loads stored exchange rate data used for currency conversions.
•	Role in System:
o	Acts as the historical market data ingestion layer, downloading and storing price and dividend data that the trading engine uses for backtesting and analysis.



 
File: price_service.py (Portfolio Calculation Module)
•	Purpose: Calculates portfolio values, performance metrics, dividends, and cash positions based on transaction history and historical market data.
•	Inputs:
o	Transaction records (buy/sell data for each stock)
o	Historical stock price data
o	Exchange rate data
o	Mapping of company names to tickers
•	Currency Handling:
o	Supports multiple currencies (USD, GBP, EUR, CAD).
o	Uses exchange rate data to convert all values into GBP for consistent portfolio valuation.
•	Position Value Calculation:
o	Calculates the current value of each position by multiplying:
shares held × latest stock price
o	Converts values to GBP using exchange rates when necessary.
o	Aggregates values to compute the total portfolio value.
•	Performance Calculations:
Weekly Performance
o	Calculates percentage return over the last week:
((recent price − price one week ago) / price one week ago) × 100
Overall Performance
o	Calculates percentage return since the first purchase date:
((current price − purchase price) / purchase price) × 100
•	Dividend Calculations:
o	Calculates total dividends earned from each stock.
o	Adjusts dividends based on number of shares held at the dividend date.
o	Converts dividends into GBP using exchange rates.
•	Portfolio Time Series:
o	Calculates daily portfolio value over time using historical stock prices.
o	Tracks how the portfolio evolves across dates.
•	Cash Position Tracking:
o	Tracks available cash in the portfolio.
o	Starts with an initial capital of £10,000.
o	Subtracts cash used to purchase stocks.
o	Adds dividends received.
•	Daily Cash Position:
o	Calculates how cash changes each day based on trades and dividends.
•	Output:
o	Portfolio valuation tables
o	Performance metrics
o	Daily portfolio values
o	Dividend totals
o	Cash position tracking
•	Data Export:
o	Combines portfolio value, cash position, and dividends into a dataset.
o	Saves the results as an Excel file containing:
	Full portfolio data
	Summary performance sheet
•	Role in System:
o	Acts as the portfolio analytics engine, calculating performance, portfolio value, dividends, and cash flows based on trading activity and historical market data.


File: price_service.py / Portfolio Calculation Module
•	Purpose: Calculates portfolio values, performance metrics, dividends, and cash balances using transaction data, historical stock prices, and exchange rates.
•	Inputs:
o	Transaction records (buy/sell history for each stock)
o	Historical stock price data
o	Exchange rate data
o	Mapping of company names to stock tickers
•	Currency Handling:
o	Supports multiple currencies (USD, GBP, EUR, CAD).
o	Uses exchange rates to convert all portfolio values into GBP for consistent reporting.
•	Position Value Calculation:
o	Calculates the value of each position using:
position value = shares held × latest stock price
o	Converts the value into GBP if the stock is traded in another currency.
o	Aggregates values to calculate the total portfolio value.
•	Performance Calculations:
Weekly Performance
o	Measures price change over the past week:
((recent price − price one week ago) / price one week ago) × 100
Overall Performance
o	Measures performance since the initial purchase:
((current price − purchase price) / purchase price) × 100
•	Dividend Calculations:
o	Calculates dividends received from each stock.
o	Adjusts for the number of shares held on each dividend date.
o	Converts dividends into GBP using exchange rates.
•	Portfolio Time Series:
o	Calculates daily portfolio values across time using historical price data.
o	Tracks how the value of each stock and the total portfolio change over time.
•	Cash Position Tracking:
o	Starts with an initial capital of £10,000.
o	Subtracts the cost of stock purchases.
o	Adds dividends received to determine the remaining cash balance.
•	Daily Cash Tracking:
o	Tracks changes in cash position for each day based on transactions and dividend payments.
•	Data Export:
o	Combines portfolio values, dividends, and cash positions into a dataset.
o	Exports results to an Excel file containing:
	Full daily portfolio data
	Summary performance metrics.
•	Role in System:
o	Acts as the portfolio analytics engine, calculating portfolio valuation, performance metrics, dividends, and cash flows from trading activity and market data.


File: universe_utils.py
•	Purpose: Manages the stock universe, defining which securities the trading engine tracks and analyzes.
•	Data Source: Uses a configuration file called universe.json, which contains information about stocks grouped by sector.
•	Inputs:
o	universe.json file containing:
	stock tickers
	company names
	sector classifications
•	Universe Loading:
o	load_universe() loads the universe.json file into the system.
•	Ticker Extraction:
o	get_all_tickers() retrieves a list of all stock tickers defined in the universe.
•	Sector Filtering:
o	get_tickers_by_sector() returns tickers belonging to a specific sector (e.g., technology, finance).
•	Ticker Information Retrieval:
o	get_ticker_info() returns detailed information for a specific ticker, including:
	ticker symbol
	company name
	sector
	sector category
•	Output:
o	Lists of stock tickers or dictionaries containing company information.
•	Role in System:
o	Defines the set of securities (the trading universe) that the engine processes for data retrieval, analysis, and portfolio calculations.


